  // ── Doc 48: Sourdough Bread Recipe ──
  createDocInFolder("Sourdough Bread Recipe", [
    "# Priya's Sourdough Bread Recipe",
    "",
    "Makes: 1 large boule (approximately 900g baked weight)",
    "Total time: 24 hours (mostly waiting — active time is about 45 minutes)",
    "Difficulty: Intermediate (your first few loaves may be imperfect, and that is fine)",
    "",
    "## Background",
    "",
    "I started baking sourdough during the pandemic in 2020 and have been refining this recipe for five years. It has become a weekend ritual — I mix the dough on Friday evening, bake on Saturday morning, and bring a loaf to the office on Monday (if there is any left). Several RavenStack team members have asked for the recipe after tasting it at team lunches, so here it is in full detail.",
    "",
    "This recipe produces a loaf with a dark, crackling crust, an open crumb with irregular holes, and a complex tangy flavor that develops during the long cold fermentation. It is inspired by Chad Robertson's Tartine method but adapted for a home oven and a busy schedule.",
    "",
    "## Essential Equipment",
    "",
    "- Kitchen scale (measuring by weight is non-negotiable for consistent results — volume measurements are unreliable for flour)",
    "- Large mixing bowl (at least 4-quart capacity)",
    "- Dutch oven with lid (cast iron preferred — Lodge 5-quart combo cooker is my recommendation, about $45 on Amazon)",
    "- Bench scraper (for handling sticky dough during shaping)",
    "- Banneton proofing basket (9-inch round — approximately $15 on Amazon; you can substitute a mixing bowl lined with a floured kitchen towel)",
    "- Lame or razor blade (for scoring the dough before baking — a sharp serrated knife works in a pinch)",
    "- Wire cooling rack",
    "- Instant-read thermometer (optional but helpful for checking internal temperature)",
    "",
    "## Ingredients",
    "",
    "- 500g bread flour (King Arthur bread flour preferred — the higher protein content gives better structure. Do not use all-purpose flour; the results will be noticeably different.)",
    "- 350g water, warm (78-80 degrees Fahrenheit / 25-27 Celsius — slightly warmer than room temperature. Warm water activates the yeast in the starter more quickly.)",
    "- 100g active sourdough starter (fed 4-8 hours before mixing — see Starter section below)",
    "- 10g fine sea salt (regular table salt works, but sea salt dissolves more evenly. Do not reduce the salt — it controls fermentation speed and develops flavor.)",
    "",
    "### About the Starter",
    "",
    "You need an active sourdough starter to make this bread. If you do not have one, you can grow one from scratch in 7-10 days (mix equal parts flour and water, discard half daily, feed with fresh flour and water, wait for bubbling activity) or get a portion from a friend who bakes.",
    "",
    "To test if your starter is ready: drop a small spoonful into a glass of water. If it floats, the starter is active and ready. If it sinks, feed it and wait another 2-4 hours.",
    "",
    "My starter is named 'Ada' (after Ada Lovelace) and is 4 years old. She lives in the fridge between baking sessions and gets a feeding 8-12 hours before I plan to mix dough.",
    "",
    "## Day 1 — Friday Evening (Active time: 30 minutes, spread over 3 hours)",
    "",
    "### Step 1: Autolyse (6:00 PM)",
    "In your large mixing bowl, combine 500g bread flour and 350g warm water. Mix with your hand until no dry flour remains — the dough will be shaggy and rough. Do not knead or try to develop gluten at this stage.",
    "",
    "Cover the bowl with a damp towel or plastic wrap and let it rest for 30-60 minutes. This rest is called the autolyse (pronounced auto-LEEZ). During the autolyse, the flour hydrates fully and gluten begins to develop on its own without any kneading. This step is optional but makes the dough significantly easier to handle later.",
    "",
    "### Step 2: Add Starter and Salt (6:45 PM)",
    "Add 100g of active starter and 10g of salt to the dough. Mix by hand: squeeze the dough through your fingers, fold it over itself, and repeat for 3-4 minutes until the starter and salt are fully incorporated. The dough will feel wet and sticky — that is correct at 70% hydration.",
    "",
    "### Step 3: Stretch and Fold (7:00 PM - 9:00 PM)",
    "Over the next 2 hours, perform 4 sets of stretch and folds, one set every 30 minutes.",
    "",
    "How to stretch and fold: with wet hands, grab one side of the dough, stretch it upward until you feel resistance (do not tear it), then fold it over to the opposite side. Rotate the bowl 90 degrees and repeat. Do this 4 times (one full rotation) per set.",
    "",
    "You will notice the dough becoming smoother and more cohesive with each set. After the first set, it will still be slack and sticky. By the fourth set, it should hold its shape briefly when you stop touching it.",
    "",
    "### Step 4: Bulk Fermentation (9:00 PM - overnight)",
    "After the final stretch and fold, cover the bowl and leave it at room temperature (68-72 degrees Fahrenheit) for 4-6 hours. The timing depends on your room temperature and starter strength.",
    "",
    "How to tell when bulk fermentation is done: the dough should have increased in volume by 50-75% (not doubled — over-fermented dough loses structure). The surface should look slightly domed and you should see some bubbles on the sides of the bowl. If you gently jiggle the bowl, the dough should move in a jelly-like way.",
    "",
    "If your kitchen is cool (below 65 degrees), bulk fermentation may take 8-10 hours. If warm (above 75 degrees), it may be done in 3-4 hours. Set an alarm if needed.",
    "",
    "## Day 2 — Saturday Morning (Active time: 15 minutes)",
    "",
    "### Step 5: Shape (8:00 AM)",
    "Turn the dough out onto a lightly floured surface (use rice flour if you have it — it does not absorb into the dough and prevents sticking better than wheat flour). Using your bench scraper, gently shape the dough into a round boule (ball shape).",
    "",
    "Shaping technique: fold the edges toward the center, flip the dough smooth-side up, and use the bench scraper to drag it toward you on the counter, creating surface tension. The bottom of the dough should stick slightly to the counter while the top skin stretches taut.",
    "",
    "Do not over-handle the dough. You want to build tension on the surface without degassing all the bubbles inside. Less is more here.",
    "",
    "### Step 6: Cold Retard (8:10 AM - when ready to bake)",
    "Place the shaped dough seam-side up in your floured banneton basket. Cover with plastic wrap or a shower cap and refrigerate for 1-12 hours. This cold retard slows fermentation and develops deeper flavor through organic acid production.",
    "",
    "You can bake anytime within the 1-12 hour window. I usually bake around 10:00 AM (2 hours of cold retard), but the dough is also great after overnight refrigeration if you want to bake on Sunday morning instead.",
    "",
    "### Step 7: Bake",
    "",
    "Preheat your oven to 500 degrees Fahrenheit with the Dutch oven inside. The Dutch oven needs at least 45 minutes to fully preheat — do not rush this step. The pre-heated Dutch oven creates the steam environment needed for a good crust.",
    "",
    "Remove the dough from the fridge. It should feel firm and cold. Turn it out onto a piece of parchment paper (seam-side down — the smooth side should now be facing up).",
    "",
    "Score the dough: using your lame or razor blade, make a confident slash about 3-4 inches long and half an inch deep at a 30-degree angle. The slash allows the bread to expand in a controlled way during the 'oven spring' (the rapid rise that happens in the first 10 minutes of baking).",
    "",
    "Carefully place the dough (on the parchment paper) into the hot Dutch oven. Cover with the lid.",
    "",
    "Bake covered: 20 minutes at 500 degrees Fahrenheit. The lid traps steam from the dough, which keeps the crust flexible and allows the bread to rise fully before the crust sets.",
    "",
    "Uncover: remove the lid, reduce temperature to 450 degrees Fahrenheit. Bake for 20-25 minutes more until the crust is deep brown (darker than you think — the Maillard reaction needs time to develop full flavor).",
    "",
    "The bread is done when the internal temperature reads 205-210 degrees Fahrenheit. If you do not have a thermometer, tap the bottom of the loaf — it should sound hollow.",
    "",
    "### Step 8: Cool",
    "Transfer the bread to a wire cooling rack. This is the hardest part: you must wait at least 1 hour before cutting. Cutting too early releases steam and makes the interior gummy. The bread is still cooking internally during the cooling period as the starches set.",
    "",
    "I know it smells incredible. I know you want to cut into it immediately. Resist. The wait is worth it.",
    "",
    "## Tips for Success",
    "",
    "- Starter should float in water when ready. If it does not, give it another feeding and wait 4-6 hours.",
    "- Wetter dough (higher hydration) produces more open crumb structure (bigger holes). This recipe is 70% hydration, which is a good starting point. Advanced bakers can try 75-80% hydration for more dramatic results, but the dough becomes significantly harder to handle.",
    "- Practice makes perfect. Your first few loaves may be dense, flat, or unevenly shaped. This is normal. The variables (starter strength, room temperature, flour brand, oven temperature accuracy) take a few bakes to calibrate.",
    "- Keep a baking log: record the room temperature, bulk fermentation time, and results for each bake. After 5-10 bakes, you will know your kitchen well enough to produce consistent results.",
    "- If the crust is too thick: reduce the covered baking time by 2-3 minutes. If the crust is too thin: increase covered time by 2-3 minutes."
  ].join("\n"), folder);


